\cf6 Hello again, Jan,\
Thanks for all the hints and materials. I hope to sort it out with your suggestions. As it stands now, I can do the precision weighting in Aitchison's log-ratio principal component analysis (LR-PCA). I just feed the log transformed compositions into wAddPCA, using both column and row adjustments, and the weight matrix just contains the reciprocals of all variances (or standard deviations) for the entries. I found those variances by using the delta method and assuming that multinomial counts underly the compositions. This seems to work.\
Because there are often different groups in the data, given by some additional categorical variable, in practice one will want to this for LR-LDA, where the precision weighting may help to discriminate groups. So that's why I need to be able to do the elementwise weighting while having LDA's term S^\{-1/2\} around. The canonical correlation case will be similar.\
The elementwise weighting offered by WALS looks especially promising in the case of parts that are rare in one group, but common in another. In that case, an overall weight for the whole column makes little sense, as precision will vary along the observations.\'a0WALS could be an alternative to the use of robust methods that have been proposed for compositional data to reduce the effect of outliers.\
I will be happy to share some draft by the time I got the elementwise weighting solved for LR-LDA.\
My latest work (attached) is on relations between genotype and allele compositions, and also shows the relationships between the LR-PCA based on genotypes or alleles. It is essentially multivariate analysis, though it may be too genetic to your taste. I sent this to a journal called Molecular Ecology Resources which is a genetics/ecology journal, but with a strong interest for methodological contributions. It got fairly positive reviews on the first round, and I expect the update will be accepted.\
Best wishes,\
Jan\'a0\
