\cf7 Hello Jan,\uc0\u8232 \u8232 Here is a bit of an update.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 Last July I finally became full professor. The internal promotion procedure has lasted been for almost two-and-a-half year, a long and burocratical way.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 I'm very much into WALS again these days. The analysis of compositions by means of Aitchison's logratio approach is, in general, outlier-prone. WALS can help by using elementwise weights, weighting the logratios by their precision. I use the inverse of the asymptotic variance of the ratios for this weighting, assuming multinomial counts that underlie the compositions. It seems to work quite sensibly for some datasets. Due to the precision weights, outliers can get pulled in, and group homogeneity can improve. I'm thinking about writing it down.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 I remember we have commented GLS based multivariate methods at some point, which seemed hard to resolve via WALS. Standard canonical correlations (CCo) and LDA can be done via WALS with unit weights simply by feeding the transformed data matrix into wAddPCA, but that is not going to work satisfactorily with non-unit weights, because of the transformation with the inverse of the covariance matrices (two in CCo, one in LDA). Did we treat these cases? It doesn't look like or I can't find it back.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 Best wishes,\uc0\u8232 \u8232 Jan\'a0\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
